For, though the praefectura annonae was one of the great offices regularly held by equites, there are instances in which senators were, for special reasons, selected to fill one or other of the praefecturae equestres1; or it may be that Paulinus, being an eques, was created a senator by imperial nomination (adlectio). The language used by Seneca² shows that Paulinus was still in the prime of life about 50 A.D. ; so it is not surprising that he should be actively employed in important posts twelve years later.

Is the Paulinus of Seneca is also the Paulinus of Tacitus, it is clear that he did not follow the advice given him, to retire from official life. But it is possible, as we shall see, that Seneca did not in the least expect that his advice would be taken.
